{
  "lesson_number": 11,
  "title": "Lesson 11",
  "topic": "Present participle (masculine and neuter)",
  "grammar": {
    "explanations": [
      "Present participles are formed by adding -nta or -māna to the verbal base. They function as adjectives and agree in gender, number and case with the nouns they qualify.",
      "In the masculine and neuter, present participles are declined like -a ending nouns. (The feminine gender of the present participle will be explained in Lesson 21.)",
      "Examples of present participle formation: paca + nta/māna = pacanta/pacamāna (cooking); gaccha + nta/māna = gacchanta/gacchamāna (going); bhuñja + nta/māna = bhuñjanta/bhuñjamāna (eating); tiṭṭha + nta/māna = tiṭṭhanta/tiṭṭhamāna (standing); vihara + nta/māna = viharanta/viharamāna (dwelling).",
      "The present participle can be declined in all cases to agree with the nouns they qualify."
    ],
    "tables": [],
    "examples": [
      {
        "pali": "Bhattaṃ pacanto / pacamāno puriso hasati.",
        "english": "The man who is cooking rice laughs. (Nom. case, singular)"
      },
      {
        "pali": "Vejjo bhattaṃ pacantaṃ / pacamānaṃ purisaṃ pakkosati.",
        "english": "The doctor calls the man who is cooking rice. (Acc. case, singular)"
      },
      {
        "pali": "Vejjo bhattaṃ pacantena / pacamānena purisena saha bhāsati.",
        "english": "The doctor speaks with the man who is cooking rice. (Inst. case, singular)"
      },
      {
        "pali": "Bhattaṃ pacantā / pacamānā purisā hasanti.",
        "english": "The men who are cooking rice laugh. (Nom. case, plural)"
      },
      {
        "pali": "Vejjo bhattaṃ pacante / pacamāne purise pakkosati.",
        "english": "The doctor calls the men who are cooking rice. (Acc. case, plural)"
      },
      {
        "pali": "Vejjo bhattaṃ pacantehi / pacamānehi purisehi saha bhāsati.",
        "english": "The doctor speaks with the men who are cooking rice. (Inst. case, plural)"
      }
    ]
  },
